original_kernel_variant.question:
Let $n\ge 2$ be an integer and let $p$ be a prime with $p>n$.  
Assume moreover that $p\equiv 1 \pmod n$ so that the finite field $\mathbb F_{p}$ contains a primitive $n$-th root of unity $\zeta$ (that is, $\zeta^{\,n}=1$ and $\zeta^{\,k}\neq 1$ for $1\le k<n$).

For every vector  
\[
e=(e_{1},\dots ,e_{n})\in(\mathbb Z/n\mathbb Z)^{n}
\]
define the linear form  
\[
L_{e}(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})=\zeta^{e_{1}}x_{1}
                     +\zeta^{e_{2}}x_{2}
                     +\dots
                     +\zeta^{e_{n}}x_{n},
\qquad 
s(e)=e_{1}+e_{2}+\dots +e_{n}\in\mathbb Z/n\mathbb Z .
\]

(a)  (Fourier-polarisation identity)  
Prove that in the ring $\mathbb F_{p}[x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}]$
\[
\boxed{\;
x_{1}x_{2}\cdots x_{n}
=\frac{1}{n!\,n^{\,n}}
\sum_{e\in(\mathbb Z/n\mathbb Z)^{n}}
\zeta^{-\,s(e)}\,L_{e}(x)^{\,n}}\tag{$\ast$}
\]

(b)  Compression to lower order roots.  
Let $m$ be a positive divisor of $n$ and write $n=m\ell$.  Put $\eta=\zeta^{\,\ell}$, a primitive $m$-th root of unity in $\mathbb F_{p}$.  
For $\varepsilon=(\varepsilon_{1},\dots ,\varepsilon_{n})\in(\mathbb Z/m\mathbb Z)^{n}$ set
\[
M_{\varepsilon}(x)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\eta^{\varepsilon_{i}}x_{i},
\qquad
s(\varepsilon)=\varepsilon_{1}+\dots +\varepsilon_{n}\in\mathbb Z/m\mathbb Z .
\]
Show that
\[
\boxed{\;
x_{1}\cdots x_{n}
=\frac{1}{n!\,m^{\,n}}
\sum_{\varepsilon\in(\mathbb Z/m\mathbb Z)^{n}}
\eta^{-\,s(\varepsilon)}\,M_{\varepsilon}(x)^{\,n}}\tag{$\ast\ast$}
\]

In particular, if $n$ is even one may take $m=2$ (so $\eta=-1$) and obtain the binary kernel identity
\[
\boxed{\;
x_{1}\cdots x_{n}
=\frac{1}{n!}
\sum_{(\varepsilon_{1},\dots ,\varepsilon_{n})\in\{0,1\}^{n}}
(-1)^{\,n-(\varepsilon_{1}+\dots +\varepsilon_{n})}
\bigl(\varepsilon_{1}x_{1}+\dots +\varepsilon_{n}x_{n}\bigr)^{\,n}}\tag{$\dagger$}
\]

(c)  Representation-theoretic meaning of $(\ast)$.  
Let $V$ be the $\mathbb F_{p}$-vector space with basis $\{x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}\}$ and let $S_{n}$ act by place-permutation.  
Regard $z\mapsto z^{\,n}$ as the element of $\operatorname{Sym}^{n}(V)$ obtained from the identity map $z\mapsto z$ by taking $n$-th powers.  
Show that the right-hand side of $(\ast)$ is the $S_{n}$-equivariant projection of the element $z\mapsto z^{\,n}$ onto the \emph{trivial} one-dimensional subrepresentation of $\operatorname{Sym}^{n}(V)$ generated by $x_{1}\cdots x_{n}$.

(d)  Minimal number of $\zeta$-forms.  
A linear form of the shape $L_{e}$ will be called a \emph{$\zeta$-form}.  
Let $r(n)$ be the smallest integer $t$ for which one can write
\[
x_{1}\cdots x_{n}
=\sum_{j=1}^{t}c_{j}\,L_{e(j)}(x)^{\,n},
\qquad c_{j}\in\mathbb F_{p}.
\]
Using Apolarity Theory prove the lower bound
\[
\boxed{\;r(n)\;\ge\;2^{\,n-1}}\tag{$\dagger\dagger$}
\]

Consequently the explicit decomposition $(\ast)$---which employs $n^{\,n}$ summands---is optimal up to the factor
\[
\frac{n^{\,n}}{2^{\,n-1}}=\Bigl(\tfrac{n}{2}\Bigr)^{\!n}.
\]

(All denominators are invertible in $\mathbb F_{p}$ because $p>n$.)
